            <h3>Understanding Japanese Phonetics for Names</h3>
            <p>Japanese uses a mora-based phonetic system rather than syllables. Each mora represents one rhythmic beat — for example, "ka" (カ) is one mora, while the long vowel in "kā" (カー) counts as two morae. When converting English names, certain sounds that don't exist in Japanese are adapted: "L" becomes "R" (ル), "V" becomes "B" (ブ), and consonant clusters are broken with vowels. The name "Smith" becomes スミス (Su-mi-su) because Japanese doesn't allow consonant clusters.</p>

            <p>Japanese honorific suffixes like -san (さん), -chan (ちゃん), -kun (くん), and -sama (さま) are commonly added after names to show respect or familiarity. These naming conventions are an important part of Japanese culture and social hierarchy.</p>

            <h3>Common Uses for Your Japanese Name</h3>
            <p>People convert their names to Japanese for many purposes: designing a name tattoo in authentic Japanese calligraphy (書道, shodō), creating a personal seal or stamp called hanko (判子) or inkan (印鑑), printing Japanese business cards (名刺, meishi), personalizing gaming usernames and social media profiles, or simply exploring Japanese language and culture. Many travelers to Japan also find it useful for hotel registrations and restaurant reservations where katakana is expected for foreign names.</p>
